s set at the <b data-path-to-node=3D"10" data-index-in-node=3D"264">second =
level (1-2 seconds)</b>, this provided a certain buffer for the architectur=
al design. Instead of opting for an extreme millisecond-level low latency c=
onfiguration, I set the <b data-path-to-node=3D"10" data-index-in-node=3D"4=
41">Flink Checkpoint interval to 5 minutes</b> and enabled <b data-path-to-=
node=3D"10" data-index-in-node=3D"492">Unaligned Checkpoints</b>. This deci=
sion significantly mitigated the risk of backpressure caused by network ali=
gnment in high-concurrency scenarios.</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"11">Simult=
aneously, for the Kafka cluster, I designed <b data-path-to-node=3D"11" dat=
a-index-in-node=3D"50">128 partitions</b>, ensuring sufficient horizontal s=
calability before data enters the computing engine. To maintain the stabili=
ty of second-level latency, I specifically optimized <b data-path-to-node=
=3D"11" data-index-in-node=3D"226">Flink's Watermark generation strategy</b=
>, adopting a heuristic algorithm with periodic generation and setting the =
out-of-order tolerance to 3 seconds. This not only covered common jitters c=
aused by global network transmission but also ensured that the digital upda=
tes on the frontend dashboard remained smooth and accurate under heavy traf=
fic surges."</p><hr data-path-to-node=3D"12"><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"13">=
